author: Ravin_Agrawal;
title: 10 young Indian artists to watch

aws-transcripts.transcript: right now is the most exciting time to see new Indian art. Contemporary artists in India are having a conversation with the world like never before. I thought it might be interesting, even for the many longtime collectors here with us Ted, local collectors tohave an outside view of 10 young Indian artists. I wish everyone had Ted to know first is Barty care. The central motif of Bharti's practice is the Ready made, a store bought bendy that untold millions of Indian women applied their foreheads every day in an act closely associated with the institution of marriage. But originally, the significance of the bendy is symbolized the third eye between the spiritual world and the religious world. Bharti seeks deliberate this everyday cliche, as she calls it, by exploding it into something spectacular. She also creates life size fiberglass sculptures, often of animals, which he then completely covers in been these often with potent symbolism, she says she first got started with 10 packets have been these, and then wondered what she could do with 10,000. Our next artist, Balasubramaniam, really stands at the crossroads of sculpture, painting and installation, working wonders with fiberglass since Bala himself will be speaking at Ted. I won't spend too much time on him here today, except to say that he really succeeds and making the invisible, visible. Brooklyn based Chitra Ganache is known for her digital collages using Indian comic books called Amar Chitra Kolkata's as her primary source material. These comics are a fundamental way the children, especially in the diaspora, learn their religious and mythological folk tales. I, for one, was steeped in these Chitra basically remixes and re titles, these iconic images to tease out some of the sexual and gender politics embedded in these deeply influential comics, and she uses his vocabulary in her installation work as well. Jeff Fish colored successfully practices across photography, sculpture, painting and installation. As you can see, he's heavily influenced by graffiti and street art, and his home city of Mumbai is an ever present element in his work. He really captures that sense of density and energy, which really characterizes modern urban Bombay. He also creates phantasmagoric sculptures made of bones from cast resin. Here he envisions the carcass of an auto rickshaw he once witnessed burning in a riot. This next artist s Harsha actually has a studio right here in my store. He's putting a contemporary spin on the miniature tradition. He creates these fine, delicate images, which he then repeats on a massive scale. He uses scale to more and more spectacular effect, whether on the roof of a temple in Singapore or it is increasingly ambitious installation work here. With 192 functioning sewing machines fabricating the flags of every member of United Nations, Mumbai based Groovy, Acharya builds on her love of comic books and street art to comment on the rolls and expectations of modern Indian women. She two minds. The rich source material of a merchant. Ricotta has been a very different way than trip through Gyanesh. In this particular work, she actually strips out the images and leaves the actual text to reveal something previously unseen and provocative. Ricky Pshaw is cocotte, the born Kashmir raised in London trained. He, too, is reinventing the miniature tradition. He creates these opulent tableaus inspired by Hieronymus Bosch but also by the Kashmiri textiles of his youth.
